more explanation why we make both variable and cosntructor private with coding : 

If in a singleton class, the variable and constructor are public, how can we initialize values from another class?

If both variable and constructor are public, then:

-> Any class can call new Singleton(), which breaks the Singleton pattern.

-> So, you’re no longer following Singleton rules.
	

Why Singleton Fails in This Case?

❌ Example (Incorrect Singleton):
public class Singleton {
    public static Singleton instance = null;  // public variable
    public Singleton() {                      // public constructor
        System.out.println("Constructor called");
    }
}
	
Now from another class:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Singleton s1 = new Singleton(); // ❌ creates a new object
        Singleton s2 = new Singleton(); // ❌ creates another object
    }
}

👉 So here, multiple objects are created — Singleton is broken.


Correct Singleton Pattern:

To properly follow Singleton, do this:
	public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance = null;   // ✅ static variable
    private Singleton() {                       // ✅ private constructor
        System.out.println("Constructor called");
    }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {     // ✅ global access method
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

Now from another class:

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Singleton s1 = Singleton.getInstance();  // ✅ Only one object
        Singleton s2 = Singleton.getInstance();  // ✅ Same object
    }
}


| Scenario                                 | Result                                |
| ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Constructor is public                    | ❌ Anyone can create new object        |
| Variable is public                       | ❌ Anyone can reassign or modify       |
| Constructor **and** variable are private | ✅ Singleton is protected and enforced |
| Access object through `getInstance()`    | ✅ Only one object allowed             |


