Q : Why getInstance() is static?

Because the constructor is private, we cannot create an object using new A() from outside.

If getInstance() was not static, we’d need an object to call it like:

A obj = new A(); // ❌ Not allowed (constructor is private)// here A is a singleton class whose object we are creating here
                 // so if we create so it break the singleton rule so thats why we make the method static and call 
                 // directly by class name. 
obj.getInstance(); // ❌ Can't reach here because of the static method(getInstance) it cant call means object cant call the 
                   // static method 


But if it’s static, we can call it without an object:

A obj = A.getInstance(); ✅


This way, we directly get the single instance of the class without ever creating one manually.

	
