Q10 : what is prototype design pattern ? 
Ans : used to create new object by copying an existing object.  	
      It will give you a new object(different), but with the same data.

      Student s1 = new Student();  
      Student s2 = s1.clone();
     
      output - 
      s1  → @A9214   (example memory address)
	  s2  → @B5521   (different address)


 steps : 1 - first we have to write prototype interface which has clone abstract/incomplete method.
         2 - we have to implement this clone method in a class. which returns the existing object 
		     by using private variable.
			 
		 3 - Client(class in which we create object) - 
             the class that request the new object from the prototype by calling the clone method.
            			 
      

code : // Step 1: Create a Prototype interface
interface Prototype extends Cloneable {
    Prototype clone();
}

// Step 2: Implement the Prototype interface in a concrete class
class ConcretePrototype implements Prototype {
    private String name;

    public ConcretePrototype(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public Prototype clone() {
        try {
            return (Prototype) super.clone(); // Shallow copy
        } catch (CloneNotSupportedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
            return null;
        }
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

// Step 3: Use the Prototype pattern
public class PrototypePatternDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a prototype instance
        ConcretePrototype original = new ConcretePrototype("Original");

        // Clone the prototype
        ConcretePrototype cloned = (ConcretePrototype) original.clone();

        System.out.println("Original Name: " + original.getName());
        System.out.println("Cloned Name: " + cloned.getName());
    }
}
	
	
