Q : What is Behavioral desing pattern ?
Ans  : 
Behavioral Design Patterns (Simple Explanation)

Behavioral Design Patterns are about
👉 how objects talk to each other
👉 how they share work or responsibilities

In short:

They define how things happen in a program — who does what and how they work together.

Strategy Design Pattern – Simple Explanation:
The Strategy Design Pattern selects (or switches) the algorithm or behavior (object) at runtime — not at compile time.

The Strategy Design Pattern lets you choose different algorithms or behaviors at runtime, without changing the code that
uses them.

👉 In simple words:

It’s like having multiple ways to do something, and you can pick which way to use while the program is running.

💡 Real-life Example:

Imagine you’re using Google Maps — you can choose:

Driving route 🚗

Walking route 🚶

Cycling route 🚴

All are different strategies for finding a path.
The app just switches the strategy without changing the main code.	

Code  : 
// Step 1: Strategy Interface
interface RouteStrategy {
    void buildRoute(String start, String end);
}

// Step 2: Concrete Strategies
class DrivingRoute implements RouteStrategy {
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Building driving route from " + start + " to " + end);
    }
}

class WalkingRoute implements RouteStrategy {
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Building walking route from " + start + " to " + end);
    }
}

class CyclingRoute implements RouteStrategy {
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Building cycling route from " + start + " to " + end);
    }
}

// Step 3: Context Class
class Navigation {
    private RouteStrategy routeStrategy;

    // Change route strategy at runtime
    public void setRouteStrategy(RouteStrategy routeStrategy) {
        this.routeStrategy = routeStrategy;
    }

    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        if (routeStrategy == null) {
            System.out.println("Please select a route type first!");
        } else {
            routeStrategy.buildRoute(start, end);
        }
    }
}

// Step 4: Test the Strategy Pattern
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Navigation navigation = new Navigation();

        // Choose Driving Strategy
        navigation.setRouteStrategy(new DrivingRoute());
        navigation.buildRoute("Home", "Office");

        // Switch to Walking Strategy
        navigation.setRouteStrategy(new WalkingRoute());
        navigation.buildRoute("Home", "Park");

        // Switch to Cycling Strategy
        navigation.setRouteStrategy(new CyclingRoute());
        navigation.buildRoute("Home", "Gym");
    }
}


output  : 
Building driving route from Home to Office
Building walking route from Home to Park
Building cycling route from Home to Gym

Strategy pattern means selecting one algorithm from multiple algorithms at runtime.
Just like Google Maps gives you options (walk, bike, car), and you choose one at runtime.
The code does not change — only the strategy changes.